Sparkify Churn Analysis¶

Project Definition¶

Here we analyse a simulated event log file from a fictional Spotify-like music streaming service called Sparkify, in an attempt to predict which users churned. We define churn as a user on paid subscription downgrading to free subscription, or cancelling the service altogether.

Specifically, we will attempt to predict whether a given user churned during the 2 months covered by the data, based on their activity during this period. We will explore and clean the data, engineer any needed features, and train several classification models to determine which is best suited to the task.

Precision and recall will both be important, so the models will be evaluated based on their F-score. For example, it would be useful for a marketing department to receive a list of users likely to churn, so that a marketing intervention could take place. However, it would not be so useful if the list included lots of users who were not likely to churn, potentially incurring unnecesary expense.

This project is a capstone project from the Udacity Data Scientist nanodegree, and the data is provided by Udacity.

Loading Dataset¶

We can load a sample dataset to quickly verify the code runs correctly, or the full dataset for in-depth analysis which will take longer to complete. We partition the data according to the number of cores we expect to have available, by userID, and sorted by artist, as this optimises our feature engineering.

Set sample_data here to True for quick execution. The notebook is saved with output and commentary relating to the full dataset (sample_data False).

In [3]:
# Set sample_data as True to analyse sample dataset, or False to analyse full dataset
sample_data = False

# Set filepath and partition number relevant to the dataset
if sample_data:
    sparkify_data = "s3n://udacity-dsnd/sparkify/mini_sparkify_event_data.json"
    partitions = 24
else:
    sparkify_data = "s3n://udacity-dsnd/sparkify/sparkify_event_data.json"

def play_counts_by_user(df):
    """Count plays, aggregated by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe: Play counts, aggregated by user.
    """
    
    df = df.filter(df.page == 'NextSong') \
           .groupBy('userId') \
           .agg(F.count('page').alias('play_count'))
    
    return df

We calculate the difference between 'Thumbs Up' and 'Thumbs Down' visits as a proportion of their sum, to get an indication of whether users liked what they were hearing or not overall.

In [22]:
def page_counts_by_user(df):
    """Count visits to pages of interest, aggregated by user.

    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe: Events dataframe.
    pages: list. The pages of interest.

    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Page counts, aggregated by user.
    """

    # Count visits to each page per user
    df = df.filter(df.page.isin(pages)) \
                     .groupBy('userId') \
                     .pivot('page').count().fillna(0)

    # Rename columns for ease.
    colnames = [c.lower().replace(" ", "_") if c != 'userId' else c for c in df.columns]
    df = df.toDF(*colnames)
    
    # Subtract submit_downgrade from downgrade, and drop submit_downgrade
    df = df.withColumn('downgrade', df.downgrade - df.submit_downgrade) \
           .drop('submit_downgrade')

    return df
In [23]:
def thumbs_diff_prop_by_user(df):
    """Calculate the differences between Thumbs Up' and 'Thumbs Down' visits as a proportion of the sum, aggregated by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe: Events dataframe.

    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Differences between Thumbs Up' and 'Thumbs Down' visits as a proportion of the sum, aggregated by user.
    """
    
    df = page_counts_by_user(df)
    
    df = df.withColumn('thumbs_diff_prop', (df.thumbs_up - df.thumbs_down) / (df.thumbs_up + df.thumbs_down)) \
           .select('userId', 'thumbs_diff_prop') \
           .fillna(0)
    
    return df

We check how many users churned.

In [26]:
def churn_by_user(df):
    """Churn or not, by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Churn or not, by user.
    """
    
    is_churn = F.udf(lambda x: 1 if x == 'Cancellation Confirmation' or  x == 'Submit Downgrade' \
                                 else 0, IntegerType())
    
    df = df.withColumn('churn', is_churn(df.page)) \
           .groupBy('userId') \
           .agg(F.max('churn').alias('label')) \
           .select('userId', 'label')
    
    return df

def counts_by_user(df, col):
    """Count artists or songs played, aggregated by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    col: string. 'artist' or 'song'
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Artist or song counts, aggregated by user.
    """
    
    df = df.filter(df.page == 'NextSong') \
           .groupBy('userId') \
           .agg(F.countDistinct(col).alias(f'{col}_count')) \
           .select('userId', f'{col}_count')
    
    return df

def prop_in_top_percent_by_user(df, col, percent):
    """Calculate what minimum proportion of artists or songs played account for percent% of the song plays, aggregated by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    col: string. 'artist' or 'song'
    percent: int. Percent to calculate for.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Proportion of artists or songs played which account for percent% of the song plays, per user.
    """
    
    # Get artist count per user
    counts_by_user_df = counts_by_user(df, col)
    
    # Count number of times each user plays each artist
    df = df.filter(df.page == 'NextSong') \
           .groupBy('userId', col) \
           .count()
    
    # Set up unbounded user window
    user_window = Window.partitionBy('userId')
    
    # Calculate sum of song plays per user
    df = df.withColumn('total_count', F.sum('count').over(user_window))
    
    # Set up ordered user window, sort by descending artist popularity, and
    # artist name (to prevent ties in aggregate function)
    user_window = Window.partitionBy('userId').orderBy(F.desc('count'), col)
    
    # Calculate cumul sum of song plays per user
    df = df.withColumn('cumul_count', F.sum('count').over(user_window))
    
    # Flag which artists take song plays over percent% of total
    df = df.withColumn('under', (df.cumul_count < (df.total_count * percent / 100)).cast('integer'))
    
    # Count unflagged artists per user
    df = df.groupBy('userId') \
           .agg(F.sum('under').alias(f'{col}_count_{percent}pc'))
    
    # Add 1, for the artist that straddles the % boundary
    df = df.withColumn(f'{col}_count_{percent}pc', df[f'{col}_count_{percent}pc'] + 1)
    
    # Calculate this as a proportion of all artists listened to
    df = df.join(counts_by_user_df, 'userId')
    df = df.withColumn(f'{col}_prop_{percent}pc', df[f'{col}_count_{percent}pc'] / df[f'{col}_count']) \
           .select('userId', f'{col}_prop_{percent}pc')
    
    return df

We could potentially include some features to describe users' artist preferences. While the artists themselves are unlikely to directly influence churn, the mix of artists listened to may be indicative of other factors which are influential.

We calculate the proportion of users' songs played which were performed by each of the 1000 most popular artists. A principle component analysis may enable us to roughly distinguish between users' artist preferences using a handful of of features.

In [41]:
def get_top_artists_list(df, n_artists):
    """Gets a list of the top n_artists artists by number of plays.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Event data.
    n_artists: int. The number of artists to include.
    
    Returns:
    top_artists_list: list. The top artists in descending order.
    """
    
    # Establish top artists in descending order of song plays
    artist_play_count = df.filter(df.artist != 'None') \
                          .groupBy('artist') \
                          .count() \
                          .orderBy('count', ascending=False) \
                          .limit(n_artists) \
                          .toPandas()
    
    # Store top artist names in list
    top_artists_list = artist_play_count.artist.tolist()
    
    return top_artists_list
In [42]:
def top_artists_play_prop_per_user(df, n):
    """Calculate the proportion of plays by each of the top artists, aggregated by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    n: numeric: number to pass to get_top_artists
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Proportion of plays by each of the top artists, aggregated by user.
    artist_decode_dict: dict. key: column name, value: artist name.
    """
    
    # Get list of top artists
    top_artists_list = sc.broadcast(get_top_artists_list(df, n))
    
    # Get total plays per user
    play_counts_by_user_df = play_counts_by_user(df)
    
    # Create shortcodes to use as column names for artist features, store in dictionary keyed by artist name
    artist_encode_dict = {artist_name:f'A{i}' for (i, artist_name) in enumerate(top_artists_list.value)}
    other_artist_code = f'A{len(top_artists_list.value)}' # for anyone not in top_artists_list
    
    # Store artist names in dictionary keyed by column name (shortcode)
    artist_decode_dict = {f'A{i}':artist_name for (i, artist_name) in enumerate(top_artists_list.value)}
    artist_decode_dict[other_artist_code] = 'Other artist' # catches anyone not in top_artists_list

    # Retain user id and artist name for each play, overwrite artist name with code
    encode_artist = F.udf(lambda x: artist_encode_dict[x] if x in artist_encode_dict else other_artist_code, StringType())
    
    df = df.select('artist', 'userId').filter(df.artist != 'None') \
                                      .withColumn('artist', encode_artist(df.artist))

    # Pivot to count plays per user for each artist
    df = df.groupBy('userId').pivot('artist').count().fillna(0)
    
    # Join total plays per user
    df = df.join(play_counts_by_user_df, 'userId')
    
    # Convert artist play counts to proportions of total plays per user
    artist_colnames = list(artist_decode_dict.keys())
    df = df.select('userId', *[(df[c] / df['play_count']).alias(c) for c in artist_colnames])
                                           
    return df, artist_decode_dict

In [44]:
def vectorize_standardize_features(df):
    """Vectorize features and remove individual feature columns.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Features, by user.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Vectorized features, by user.
    """
    
    # Vectorize features
    feature_cols = [c for c in df.columns if c not in ['userId', 'label']]
    
    assembler = VectorAssembler(inputCols=feature_cols, outputCol='raw_features')
    df = assembler.transform(df)
    df = df.drop(*feature_cols)

    # Standardize features
    scaler = StandardScaler(inputCol='raw_features', outputCol='features',
                            withStd=True, withMean=True)

    scaler_model = scaler.fit(df)
    df = scaler_model.transform(df)
    df = df.drop('raw_features')
    
    return df

def male_by_user(df):
    """Male or not, by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Male or not, by user.
    """
    
    # Encode gender as male 1, female 0
    df = df.groupBy('userId', 'gender') \
           .count() \
           .withColumn('male', (df.gender == 'M').cast(IntegerType())) \
           .select('userId', 'male')
        
    return df

def registrations_by_user(df):
    """Registration timestamp, by user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Registration timestamp (numerical), by user.
    """
    
    # Encode gender as male 1, female 0
    df = df.groupBy('userId', 'registration') \
           .count() \
           .withColumn('registration', (df.registration).cast(LongType())) \
           .select('userId', 'registration')
        
    return df

def sessions_by_user(df):

In [72]:
def prop_song_played_by_play(df):
    """Calculate the proportion of each song that is actually played for each play.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Events dataframe.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Proportion of song actually played for each song play event, and userId.
    """

    # Set up a user window ordered by timestamp
    userWindow  = Window.partitionBy('userId').orderBy('ts')

    # Add the next event's timestamp to each event
    df = df.withColumn('next_ts', F.lead('ts', default=last).over(userWindow))

    # Calculate the amount of time before next event occurs
    df = df.withColumn('seconds_spent', ((df.next_ts.cast(LongType()) - df.ts.cast(LongType())) / 1000))

    # Calculate the proportion of each song that was played
    df = df.filter(df.page == 'NextSong') \
           .withColumn('prop_song_played', F.least(F.lit(1), (df.seconds_spent.cast(IntegerType()) / df.length.cast(IntegerType())))) \
           .select('userId', 'prop_song_played')

    return df

def avg_prop_song_played_by_user(df):
    """Calculate the proportion of songs skipped before the halfway point per user.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Proportion of song actually played for each song play event, and userId.
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. Proportion of songs skipped before the halfway point per user.
    """
    
    # Get proportion of each song played
    df = prop_song_played_by_play(df)
    
    # Flag which were skipped before halfway point
    df = df.withColumn('played_under_half', (df.prop_song_played < 0.5).cast('integer')) \
           .select('userId', 'played_under_half') \
           .groupBy('userId') \
           .agg(F.mean('played_under_half').alias('avg_played_under_half')) \
           .select('userId', 'avg_played_under_half')
    
    return df

Data Cleaning¶

We will need to remove rows for users that are logged out or guests, as by definition they cannot churn.

We will only need to keep the artist, page, registration, ts and userId columns for our analysis. However we will need those columns other than artist to contain values, so will drop any rows containing missing data in them.

We will also now repartition the data by user as we will regularly be joining on this column.

In [81]:
def clean_data(df):
    """Remove rows for users who are logged out or guests, remove unneeded columns,
       and drop any remaining rows with missing data other than artist.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark dataframe. The df to be cleaned
    
    Returns:
    df: pyspark dataframe. The cleaned df
    """
    
    # Retain rows for paid, logged-in/cancelling users
    df = df[(df['level'] == 'paid') & ((df['auth'] == 'Logged In') | (df['auth'] == 'Cancelled'))]
    
    # Drop unnecessary columns
    df = df.drop('level', 'auth', 'firstName', 'itemInSession', 'lastName', 'location', 'method', 'status', 'userAgent')
    
    # Drop rows with missing data in key columns
    missing_allowed = ['artist', 'length', 'song']
    df = df.dropna(subset=[c for c in df.columns if c not in missing_allowed])
    
    # Repartition by user
    df = df.repartition(partitions, 'userId').sortWithinPartitions('artist')
    
    return df

Feature Engineering¶

We will aggregate and analyse the data by user, and explore whether a principal component analysis of the artist preferences will yield useful features.

Our features at this stage will incorporate, per user:

  • total number visits to the following pages
    • 'About'
    • 'Add Friend'
    • 'Add to Playlist'
    • 'Downgrade' minus 'Submit Downgrade'
    • 'Error'
    • 'Help'
    • 'NextSong'
    • 'Roll Advert'
    • 'Save Settings'
    • 'Thumbs Up'
    • 'Thumbs Down'
  • difference between visits to 'Thumbs Up' and 'Thumbs Down' as a proportion of their sum
  • number of artists played, and the proportion of these that accounted for 25% of song plays and 50% of song plays
  • number of songs played, and the proportion of these that accounted for 25% of song plays and 50% of song plays
  • gender
  • registration timestamp
  • number of sessions
  • average songs per session
  • proportion of song plays skipped before halfway point

There will also be a binary label to indicate whether or not the user churned.

We engineer the features.

In [85]:
def engineer_features(df):
    """Aggregates events dataframe into users dataframe containing features needed for analysis
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark df. Events dataframe.

    Returns:
    df: pyspark df. Users dataframe.
    feat_names: list. Feature names in order.
    """
    
    df = churn_by_user(df).join(page_counts_by_user(df), 'userId') \
                          .join(thumbs_diff_prop_by_user(df), 'userId') \
                          .join(counts_by_user(df, 'artist'), 'userId') \
                          .join(prop_in_top_percent_by_user(df, 'artist', 50), 'userId') \
                          .join(prop_in_top_percent_by_user(df, 'artist', 25), 'userId') \
                          .join(counts_by_user(df, 'song'), 'userId') \
                          .join(prop_in_top_percent_by_user(df, 'song', 50), 'userId') \
                          .join(prop_in_top_percent_by_user(df, 'song', 25), 'userId') \
                          .join(male_by_user(df), 'userId') \
                          .join(registrations_by_user(df), 'userId') \
                          .join(sessions_by_user(df), 'userId') \
                          .join(songs_per_session_by_user(df), 'userId') \
                          .join(avg_prop_song_played_by_user(df), 'userId')
    
    feat_names = df.columns[2:]
    
    df = vectorize_standardize_features(df)
    
    return df, feat_names

Data Balancing¶

We could balance the full dataset through undersampling (as the full dataset is very large), and the sample dataset through oversampling (as the sample dataset is much smaller). However the data is close enough to being balanced already that we skip this step.

In [87]:
def balance_dataset(df, oversample=False, seed=None):
    """Balances dataset via undersampling or oversampling.
    
    Args:
    df: pyspark df. Unbalanced dataset.
    undersample: boolean. True to oversample, False to undersample (default).
    seed: int. random seed for sampling

    Returns:
    df: pyspark df. Balanced dataset.
    """
    
    # Split by label into separate dataframes
    major_df = df.filter(df.label == 0)
    minor_df = df.filter(df.label == 1)

    # Calculate ratio
    ratio = major_df.count() / minor_df.count()

    if oversample:
        # Take a sample of the smaller dataset - enough to make up the remainind
        # difference after multiple whole copies of the smaller dataset are combined
        minor_df_sample = minor_df.sample(False, ratio % 1, seed)
        
        # Add the sample to the larger dataset
        df = minor_df_sample.unionAll(major_df)
        
        # Add the smaller dataset as many times as needed
        for i in range(0, int(ratio)):
            df = df.unionAll(minor_df)
        print('Data oversampled.')
    else:
        # Take a sample of the larger dataset and combine with the smaller
        major_df = major_df.sample(False, 1/ratio, seed)
        df = major_df.unionAll(minor_df)
        print('Data undersampled.')

    return df

Initial Model¶

In [90]:
def display_metrics(pred_df):
    """ Calculates and displays confusion matrix, precision, recall and F-score.
    
    Args:
    pred_df: pyspark dataframe. Dataframe containing predictions column and labels column.
    
    Returns:
    precision: float.
    recall: float.
    f_score: float.   
    """
    
    # Calculate confusion matrix
    true_positive = pred_df.filter((pred_df.label == 1) & (pred_df.prediction == 1)).count()
    false_negative = pred_df.filter((pred_df.label == 1) & (pred_df.prediction == 0)).count()
    true_negative = pred_df.filter((pred_df.label == 0) & (pred_df.prediction == 0)).count()
    false_positive = pred_df.filter((pred_df.label == 0) & (pred_df.prediction == 1)).count()

    ## Calculate metrics
    precision = true_positive / (true_positive + false_positive)
    recall = true_positive / (true_positive + false_negative)
    f_score = (2 * precision * recall) / (precision + recall)

    ## Print confusion matrix and metrics
    print(f'       pred\n       T  F\nact  T {true_positive} {false_negative}\n     F {false_positive} {true_negative}\n')
    print(f'Precision: {precision}\nRecall: {recall}\n')
    print(f'F-score: {f_score}')
    
    return precision, recall, f_score

Improved Model¶

Pipeline¶

We build a pipeline to compare a logistic regression, a random forest classifier, and a gradient boosted tree classifier, each with three combinations of hyperparameters.

N.B. Rather than a grid search which would entail a great number of combinations of hyperparameters and thus long execution time, we would ideally implement a random search entailing 60 combinations, as suggested by James Bergstra and Yoshua Bengio at https://www.jmlr.org/papers/volume13/bergstra12a/bergstra12a.pdf. Here, we try only five combinations per classifier, for faster execution, and we handpick the parameter values to ensure coverage across the spread of possible values. This isn't really enough combinations to reliably find an model close to the optimum, but a greater number of truly randomised combinations could easily be added for a more thorough search of hyperparameter space.

In [93]:
# Prepare models, pipeline and parameter grid
lors = [LogisticRegression() for i in range(0, 5)]
rfs = [RandomForestClassifier() for i in range(0, 5)]
gbts = [GBTClassifier() for i in range(0, 5)]

lor_stages = []
rf_stages= []
gbt_stages = []

pipeline = Pipeline(stages=[])
param_grid = []

# Specify some combinations for logistic regression parameters
lor_params = [[10, 0, 0], [10, 0.1, 0], [10, 0.1, 0.5],
              [10, 0.1, 1], [100, 0.1, 0.5]]

# Add stages for logistic regression
for i in range(0, 5):
    lor_stages.append([lors[i]])
    lor_grid = ParamGridBuilder().baseOn({pipeline.stages:lor_stages[i]}) \
                                 .addGrid(lors[i].maxIter, [lor_params[i][0]]) \
                                 .addGrid(lors[i].regParam, [lor_params[i][1]]) \
                                 .addGrid(lors[i].elasticNetParam, [lor_params[i][2]]) \
                                 .build()
    param_grid += lor_grid

# Specify some combinations for random forest parameters
rf_params = [[2, 0.1, 1000], [6, 0.1, 300], [18, 0.1, 100],
             [18, 0.1, 300], [18, 0.5, 100]]

# Add stages for random forest
for i in range(0, 5):
    rf_stages.append([rfs[i]])
    rf_grid = ParamGridBuilder().baseOn({pipeline.stages:rf_stages[i]}) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].maxDepth, [rf_params[i][0]]) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].subsamplingRate, [rf_params[i][1]]) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].numTrees, [rf_params[i][2]]) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].maxBins, [8]) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].minInstancesPerNode, [10]) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].featureSubsetStrategy, ['sqrt']) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].seed, [42]) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].cacheNodeIds, [True]) \
                                .addGrid(rfs[i].checkpointInterval, [10]) \
                                .build()
    param_grid += rf_grid

# Specify some combinations for gradient boosted tree parameters
gbt_params = [[2, 0.2, 50], [2, 0.1, 100], [6, 0.2, 50],
              [6, 0.1, 100], [18, 0.2, 50]]

# Add stages for gradient boosted tree
for i in range(0, 5):
    gbt_stages.append([gbts[i]])
    gbt_grid = ParamGridBuilder().baseOn({pipeline.stages:gbt_stages[i]}) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].maxDepth, [gbt_params[i][0]]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].stepSize, [gbt_params[i][1]]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].maxIter, [gbt_params[i][2]]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].maxBins, [8]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].minInstancesPerNode, [10]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].featureSubsetStrategy, ['sqrt']) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].subsamplingRate, [0.1]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].seed, [42]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].cacheNodeIds, [True]) \
                                 .addGrid(gbts[i].checkpointInterval, [10]) \
                                 .build()
    param_grid += gbt_grid

Fitting and Testing¶

We fit the model on the training data using TrainValidationSplit. This is preferred over CrossValidator because of the size of the dataset - we have plenty of data so don't really need to fold and thus multiply execution time. The default metric used by MulticlassClassificationEvaluator is F-score which suits our needs as both precision and recall are important i.e. we want to identify as many of the users that churned as possible, while mistakenly including as few users that didn't churn as possible.

N.B. From this point on, exceptions will probably be thrown by thread cell monitors, but these don't affect the analysis.

Results¶

Our best model was a random forest classifier. This model gave an F-score of 0.600 to 3 d.p. on the test set, which is a small improvement on the F-score of 0.566 for the initial Logistic Regression model. However, the model still misses many churns, and includes many non-churns in its predicted churns.

Best Model Parameters¶

The parameters for the best random forest classifer were as follows:

  • maxDepth: 18
  • subsamplingRate: 0.5
  • numTrees: 100
  • maxBins: 8
  • minInstancesPerNode: 10
  • featureSubsetStrategy: 'sqrt'

maxDepth¶

We tried several values for tree depth, and the greatest, 18, performed best. It's possible that greater values would perform better, but this would come at a cost in execution time. For an ensemble method designed around large numbers of weak learners, we would expect the optimal tree depth to be fairly shallow. In this instance though, more numerous, weaker learners didn't perform quite as well.

subsamplingRate¶

We tried two values for the proportion of rows sampled for each tree, and the greatest, 0.5, performed best. This could be due to reduced bias in individual trees.

numTrees¶

We tried several values for the number of decision trees to grow, balancing this against the depth of the trees. However, even with a tree of the same depth, 100 trees outperformed 300 trees, so it's unlikely that adding more trees would increase performance.

maxBins, minInstancesPerNode, featureSubsetStrategy¶

These parameters were set based on research rather than experimentation. With more compute time, they could also be explored and optimised.

Overall¶

It should be noted that the validation performance for the random forest classifiers was actually very similar despite the differences in parameters. The most impactful parameter from this limited experiment was maxDepth, but still, a different train/test split might have yielded a different best model.

Overall, the models performed similarly, with the exception of logistic regression model 4, which had elasticNetParam set to 1 - effectively setting regularisation to an L1 penalty. It seems that this resulted in important parameters being eliminated.

The best gradient boosted tree classifiers had the shallowest trees. The execution time is unfortunately much longer for gradient boosted trees than the other models tested, so we weren't able to test large numbers of iterations, which may have performed better.

However, given the closeness of the scores above despite quite large differences in parameters, it seems unlikely that a model taking far longer to execute will be justified by the improvement in score.

With thumbs_diff_prop and avf_played_under_half both amongst the most important features, it seems that the most influential factor on whether a user will churn is how much they like the music.

The number of adverts played is also influential, and previous visits to the downgrade page indicate churn may be imminent.

Interestingly, features relating to the number of songs played were the least influential factors.

Conclusion¶

We set out to predict whether paid users churned (i.e. downgraded or cancelled) from the Sparkify service during a 2 month period, based on their activity throughout the period. Our final model, a random forest classifier, did manage to make correct predictions for the majority of users, but leaves room for improvement, with an F-score of 0.600 to 3 d.p.

It turned out that users' enjoyment of the music was an influential factor in whether or not they churned, as inferred from the proportion of thumbs ups to thumbs downs and the proportion of songs which were skipped.

The number of ads that were played was also influential, and users that had already visited the downgrade page in the past were more likely to go back and complete the action.

Overall usage in terms of number of songs played was not particularly influential.

Potential improvements¶

Some potential features were left out of the model, because the overall number of features, and the execution time, would have exploded quite dramatically. These features included location, browsing agent, and artist preferences. These could be explored in greater depth, perhaps distilled with a cluster analysis for example.

In the real world however, even a more successful version of this model may not be particularly useful, because by definition it isn't really predictive for the future - it's trained to classify users that haven't yet churned as secure. In reality, all future churns must come from this group. It may even be the case that many of those users incorrectly predicted to churn did indeed churn in the following weeks.

A more useful model might train on data over a longer time period, for example two years, and predict for each week which users will churn in the near future, based on both overall usage patterns, and the change in those patterns over time.
